Let $R$ be the desired matrix.  Then
\[\mathbf{v}' = R \mathbf{v}.\]Let $A$ be the matrix corresponding to rotating by $60^\circ$ counterclockwise, so
\[A = \begin{pmatrix} \cos 60^\circ & -\sin 60^\circ \\ \sin 60^\circ & \cos 60^\circ \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 1/2 & -\sqrt{3}/2 \\ \sqrt{3}/2 & 1/2 \end{pmatrix}.\]Then
\[\mathbf{v}' = A A \mathbf{v} = A^2 \mathbf{v}.\]Hence,
\[R = A^2 = \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} -1/2 & -\sqrt{3}/2 \\ \sqrt{3}/2 & -1/2 \end{pmatrix}}.\]

